arXiv.abstract:
It remains to be determined experimentally if massive neutrinos are Majorana or Dirac particles. In this connection, it has been recently suggested that the detection of cosmic neutrino background of left-handed neutrinos $
u^{}_{m L}$ and right-handed antineutrinos $\overline{
u}^{}_{m R}$ in future experiments of neutrino capture on beta-decaying nuclei (e.g., $
u^{}_e + {^3{m H}} 	o {^3}{m He} + e^-$ for the PTOLEMY experiment) is likely to distinguish between Majorana and Dirac neutrinos, since the capture rate is twice larger in the former case. In this paper, we investigate the possible impact of right-handed neutrinos on the capture rate, assuming that massive neutrinos are Dirac particles and both right-handed neutrinos $
u^{}_{m R}$ and left-handed antineutrinos $\overline{
u}^{}_{m L}$ can be efficiently produced in the early Universe. It turns out that the capture rate can be enhanced at most by $28\%$ due to the presence of relic $
u^{}_{m R}$ and $\overline{
u}^{}_{m L}$ with a total number density of $95~{m cm}^{-3}$, which should be compared to the number density $336~{m cm}^{-3}$ of cosmic neutrino background. The enhancement has actually been limited by the latest cosmological and astrophysical bounds on the effective number of neutrino generations $N^{}_{m eff} = 3.14^{+0.44}_{-0.43}$ at the $95\%$ confidence level. For illustration, two possible scenarios have been proposed for thermal production of right-handed neutrinos in the early Universe.

We study the rare semileptonic decays of $B$ mesons induced by $b 	o s 
u  ar{
u}$ as well as $b 	o s l^+ l^-$ transitions in the scalar leptoquark model where the leptoquarks transform as $(3,2,7/6)$ and $(3,2,1/6)$ under the standard model gauge group. The leptoquark parameter space is constrained using the most recent experimental results on ${m Br}(B_s ightarrow \mu^+ \mu^-)$ and ${m Br}(B_d 	o X_s \mu^+ \mu^-)$ processes. Considering only the baryon number conserving leptoquark interactions, we estimate the branching ratios for the exclusive $ ar{B} ightarrow  ar{K}^{(*)} 
u  ar{
u}$ and inclusive $B ightarrow X_s 
u  ar{
u}$ decay processes by using the constraint parameters. We also obtain the low recoil (large lepton invariant mass, i.e., $q^2 \sim m^2_b$) predictions for the angular distribution of $ ar B ightarrow  ar{K} l^+ l^-$ process and several other observables including the flat term and lepton flavour non-universality factor in this model.

Recent experimental results from the LHCb, BaBar and Belle collaborations on the semitauonic decays of $B$ meson, $ ar{B}ightarrow D^{(\ast)}	au  ar{
u}$, showing a significant deviation from the Standard Model (SM), hint towards a new physics scenario beyond the SM. In this work, we show that these enhanced decay rates can be explained within the framework of $E_{6}$ motivated Alternative Left-Right Symmetric Model (ALRSM), which has been successful in explaining the recent CMS excesses and has the feature of accommodating high scale leptogenesis. The R-parity conserving couplings in ALRSM can contribute universally to both $ ar{B}ightarrow D 	au  ar{
u}$ and $ ar{B}ightarrow D^{(\ast)}	au  ar{
u}$ via the exchange of scalar leptoquarks. We study the leptonic decays $D_{s}^{+} ightarrow 	au^{+}  ar{
u}$, $B^{+}ightarrow 	au^{+}  ar{
u}$, $D^{+}ightarrow 	au^{+}  ar{
u}$ and $D^{0}$-$ ar{D}^{0}$ mixing to constrain the couplings involved in explaining the enhanced $B$ decay rates and we find that ALRSM can explain the current experimental data on $\mathcal{R}(D^{(\ast)})$ quite well while satisfying these constraints.
